\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 We\rquote re in Lescun, on 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
 August, 2002, and we are going to record the life story of Daniel Bertaux.  So, Daniel, can we start by talking about your family background?  Maybe if you took your mother\rquote s side first?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Well, my father
\rquote s side has been more important.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Well, that\rquote 
s why I thought maybe you\rquote d take your mother\rquote s side first!
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15411510 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Okay!  Okay.  So my mother was I think the eldest daughter of six children, of Jules Supervielle who, himself, was a poet \endash 
 actually became a rather famous poet in France \endash  but originally was the son of a banker in Montevideo in Uruguay \endash 
 a French banker, it was a French family emigrated to Uruguay.  There was quite a lot of money.  The money was made there, I think in the 1860s or 1870s, by people who actually come from this region here, where we are now, the B\'e9
arn, they came from Oleron St. Mari}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411510 e.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 It\rquote 
s a long story.  But originally, what happened, the youngest son fled the family and migrated to Brazil, and went down to a place called Montevideo, when there was almost noth
ing there, or just beginning, open a shop for changing money, and eventually became - started [making] some money.  And then his elder brother had been [sent] to fetch him, and died on the way somewhere in Brazil \endash 
 he learnt about it months later.  So he came back to Oleron and completely divulged it, and asked forgiveness to his parents - he was, by that time, perhaps was 20, had been gone for four years or something.  And so when he was forgiven, then he said, 
\'93Okay, now, I\rquote m going back there.  There\rquote s good business to do.  But give me some money\'94 - or \'93Give me some jewels\'94
, because they were, they were in jewellery also, clocks and jewellery.  And so he went there and he opened the bank actually.  And as he was the first bank in Montevideo, so this guy was extremely active, and he made a great f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411510 ortune.  Made a fortune there.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
He brought [out] a young woman from his village, to marry him, and later on the sister of this woman married his young brother, and they joined him in Montevideo. And they had a baby, who was my grandfather \endash 
 Julio - Jules.  And then their father died in Oleron, so the young couple took the boat to come back, to go to the funeral \endash  the elder brother, who had all the money, remained, and they died on the way. They both died on the boat,
 probably from cholera or something, so the little boy, the little baby was adopted by his uncle, and was not told they were not his biological parents.  He learned it casually when he was either 10, or 12 or 14, and it was a tremendous shock.  Although h
e
 had been feeling something, that he was a bit different from the others. So the formation probably of his sensibility as a writer, as a poet - of course, as I see it as a sociologist, a lot of people have a sensitivity to become writers or poets. I think
, at some point, I had that.  I really wanted to become a writer.  The problem is that\rquote 
s only the subjective part, then you have the further objective part.  If you have a fortune, it haunts you.  If you have a big bank behind you, then you become a writer.  Or like Paul C\'e9
zanne, who could paint all his life, because his father was a banker.  Now, if you don\rquote t have that support, that sponsorship, well then you have a choice, either you don\rquote t marry, you never have children, you don\rquote 
t ever have responsibility, and you can become an artist, try your luck.  And if you don\rquote t, which was my case, well, then you have to find some way to make a living.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12928687 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
So you knew Jules Supervielle?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
Yes.  I knew him a little.  If I push a bit far, I would say he did not know me.  He was into his own writing.  He died in 1961, I was 20, but I don\rquote 
t remember much of him.  We usually came with my mother to visit him.  His wife was protecting him very much, his intimacy, so we used to have tea, and then adults were talking together, and we were sort of sitting on the floor and staying quiet, and that
\rquote s about all I remember of him.  It has no real influence on me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
Except for becoming a model as a writer?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
No, not at all.  No, no, not at all.  Indirectly, if you
 want, there was some influence, if I think about it, through my mother, because my mother has a personality which was shaped by this family background.  But directly now, I would say no.  No, he was never a model for me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
And what sort of poetry did he write, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 It\rquote s \'85 it
\rquote s a rather unique combination of a cosmic view \endash  the cosmos is always present, it\rquote s very often present there, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 les astres
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 , the universe - and of the inner feeling and emotion of a person.  Sometime, well, it\rquote s very good poetry.  So, he\rquote 
s usually considered as just slightly lower level than the famous Louis Aragon and Paul Eluard, so Jules Supervielle is less well-known. But school children get to read their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6111659 poetries, and he\rquote s now been in \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 La Pl\'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6111659 iade\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 , this famous collection}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6111659  of great writers.  There is a \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 La Pl\'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6111659 iade\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687  on him, with his complete works, so that\rquote 
s really the consecration.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
And so the family wealth, to some extent, descended to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
Mmm. No, the family wealth disappeared.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Disappeared?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
Disappeared in 1940. Because when France lost to Germany in this Blitzkrieg in May, 1940, \'85 There were two banks in Montevideo, there was the Italian bank, who was a rival of the French bank \endash  the Banque Supervielle.  And the Italian Bank 
\endash  this is so good a story that my mother tells me \endash 
 the Italian bank, banker, spread the rumour that the Banque Superielle lost all its assets which were invested in France, so everybody run to pick up their money from the bank, which is the en
d of the bank.  And probably because of family law, the bank was closed. All the people got, eventually, their money, but it took one or two years. There was no money stolen, nobody was \'85
 but, but that was the end of the bank.  So the Banque Supervielle still exists in Argentina, I think, but I don\rquote 
t think it belongs to the family now.  Anyhow, the money was lost.  Also, Jules Supervielle had the difficulties, he must have been, by that time, 55 or 60 perhaps, 50, but he was famous already.  Well, you don\rquote t
 make much money, but, for instance, he could write plays, or he translated Shakespeare, some of Shakespeare\rquote s plays, like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
As You Like It}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 , he translated it into French. Apparently he make more money in theatre than in poetry.  So he survive, was okay.  The
y kept on having this bourgeois way of life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411510 Paul}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid15411510 :}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411510 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 And what about his wife, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
His wife, Pilar, Pilar Sabela Cervantes-Isabella, she was from a very upper class family, apparently, with roots both in Argentina and in Brazil. Direct roots to o
ne of the most famous politicians in Argentina, who had to flee the country because of some Argentinian dictator, so he took refuge in Montevideo, and he married, apparently, the daughter of a very famous Brazilian admiral, l\rquote 
Amiral Baroso.  So they were r
eally upper class. They had 14 children, and Pilar was one of them, and they were raised by this very authoritarian mother, who had a long stick, and just could punish any child, around the table, without getting up!  Just touching them!  (LAUGHS)  So she
 was a quite strict woman who protected her husband from the noise of the children and everything.  My mother once was interviewed on television, not many years ago, and they were asking her, \'93How does it feel to be the daughter of a famous poet?\'94
  And she said, \'93Oh well, I mean, he hardly took notice of us. We used to walk on the streets, on one sidewalk, if they were walking on the other sidewalk, we had to go on the other side of the street, not to bother him\'94.  Oh no, I\rquote m not fair
\'94, she said.  She added, \'93I\rquote m not fair.  Now, from time to time he counted us\'94.  Which explains everything!  Then, of course, when she saw the interview on television, she laughed, and she say, \'93Why did I say that?  That\rquote 
s going too far.  He was kind with us from time to time\'94.  So, I mean, Pilar was completely drawn towards her husband, so she had no influence at all on me.  Most of them are buried in Oleron.  Have you been to the cemetery?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 No?  It\rquote 
s nice, because it\rquote s the old cemetery of Oleron, right here.  And on top of a hill, green hill, and their tomb is there, citrus green tomb.  There is a stone on which there are two verses of Jules Supervielle, which my father actually chose, \'93}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Ce doit ici le relais, Ou l\rquote \'e2me change de chevaux}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 \'94.  \'93This must be the stage, where the soul changes horses.\'94 He died in 1960, and she died in 1976 probably.  She, she lived quite - quite old.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 
Now, it sounds like your mother tells the story of the family.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15411510 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Daniel:\tab 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12928687\charrsid12928687 Yes, that\rquote s completely true.  My mother.  I know my uncle and aunts, but it\rquote 
s my mother.  My mother was a great storyteller of family histories actually, ever since I\rquote ve known her.  And that probably, somehow, influenced me sub-consciously, because I must confess, I\rquote m ash
amed to confess that I did not consider my mother as an intellectual at all.  I took the position of my own father towards her, which was she had no higher education, she had the baccalaur\'e9
at, but she was - she came from a very bourgeois world and, well, p
eople had money and they just enjoyed their money, they did not to work. So there was never a question for her to take up a job.  It was even in the contrary, in that generation of hers, perhaps of older people, they were rentiers, people were rentiers, a
